WEBVTT

00:00.194 --> 00:01.897
Good morning, Menlo Church.

00:02.537 --> 00:04.400
It is so good to be with you.

00:04.781 --> 00:05.642
My name is Dravon.

00:06.003 --> 00:07.745
I serve as one of the executive pastors here.

00:08.106 --> 00:18.061
And so I want to warmly welcome everyone joining us in Menlo Park, San Mateo, Mountain View, and Saratoga, as well as everyone joining us online.

00:18.081 --> 00:19.342
It's so good to have you with us.

00:19.383 --> 00:29.778
As we continue in our series, Love is where we're exploring what the topic of love is in the culture versus what the scriptures say about love.

00:30.114 --> 00:36.945
Before we do that and delve into God's word about love, I would love to come before the Lord in prayer.

00:37.025 --> 00:40.811
So would you join me in prayer as we seek what God would have for us today?

00:41.672 --> 00:55.154
Heavenly Father, thank you so much for an opportunity to come before you, to learn more about what true love is, to learn more about your love for us.

00:55.778 --> 01:00.448
Lord, there's are a lot of different things in our personal and individual lives.

01:00.989 --> 01:03.976
There are things that are going on in our families lives.

01:04.477 --> 01:06.862
There are things that are going on in our communities.

01:06.943 --> 01:13.938
There are things that are going on all around the world, Lord, that we need your definition of what love is.

01:14.402 --> 01:30.564
So wherever anyone is in this conversation of love, whether they're someone who's married, whether they're someone who is currently single, or someone who has lost a spouse, or they're navigating it, or they've decided to never marry or be in a relationship.

01:30.604 --> 01:37.514
Lord, I pray that by your grace, you would grant everyone some encouragement in the truth of what you have for us.

01:38.215 --> 01:43.602
We thank you for all of these things, and it's in Jesus' good name, we pray.

01:43.778 --> 01:44.399
Man.

01:44.419 --> 01:54.612
Now, if I asked you to actually define love today, you might offer a deep theological answer, especially since we're here in church.

01:54.632 --> 02:03.324
But if you're like me, you know, when I think about love, in my mind goes to a specific synth beat from a song from 1998.

02:04.145 --> 02:06.769
You know the song by the artist, Haddaway, right?

02:06.889 --> 02:08.070
You guys know who Haddaway is?

02:08.511 --> 02:08.731
You know?

02:09.072 --> 02:09.933
What is love?

02:10.714 --> 02:12.016
Baby, don't hurt me.

02:12.196 --> 02:13.778
Come on, all across every campus is.

02:14.050 --> 02:14.571
Here we go.

02:15.031 --> 02:19.618
When I see what is love across all our campuses, I want you to repeat the next lines.

02:19.658 --> 02:20.299
All right, you ready?

02:21.140 --> 02:22.061
What is love?

02:24.705 --> 02:25.386
Uh-huh.

02:25.406 --> 02:26.548
Don't hurt me.

02:27.169 --> 02:27.730
No more.

02:28.811 --> 02:29.652
You guys got it.

02:29.692 --> 02:30.393
You guys nailed it.

02:31.054 --> 02:32.877
But nobody gets a Grammy, but that's okay.

02:33.418 --> 02:34.018
That's okay.

02:34.599 --> 02:42.130
You know, or you think of the song, How to Way, but it was also made really famous by the movie, The Night at the Roxbury with the head bob.

02:42.658 --> 02:44.601
of Will Ferrell and Chris Catan.

02:45.081 --> 02:49.167
Now, again, remember, we're just saying the second lines of baby don't hurt me.

02:49.728 --> 02:51.110
Baby don't hurt me no more.

02:51.751 --> 02:55.576
Now, just in case you didn't know, this is not a song about love or joy.

02:55.877 --> 02:57.539
It's actually a song about fear.

02:58.180 --> 03:06.271
It's a song about love as the definition, not as sacrifice, but it's actually a plea for survival.

03:06.932 --> 03:11.218
The song defines love as a defensive posture.

03:11.682 --> 03:16.510
Please don't destroy me while I'm having a good time.

03:17.371 --> 03:27.047
Often high-paced, high-pressure places like that even here in the Bay, if we are not careful, we can even internalize this fear.

03:27.808 --> 03:39.026
This fear that can be in any type of relationship, either with family members or with friends and on the topic of dating, which it also applies.

03:39.554 --> 03:48.784
Many in our culture today, when we start dating, it's if we're not careful, it actually can become a unhinged trip to the grocery store.

03:49.085 --> 03:50.746
Now somebody's like, what does that mean?

03:50.766 --> 03:52.428
Now, we all know what that's like.

03:52.689 --> 03:55.952
When you're absolutely starving, you know the feeling.

03:56.173 --> 04:01.178
When you hit that grocery store, you're hungry for everything and everything looks great to eat.

04:01.959 --> 04:04.021
Your filter all of a sudden disappears.

04:04.542 --> 04:06.604
All of a sudden you'll want to eat things like lentils.

04:06.724 --> 04:08.306
God forbid, why?

04:08.738 --> 04:10.220
or great nuts for cereal.

04:10.280 --> 04:11.261
God, why?

04:11.482 --> 04:16.629
That's when you know when you're a difficult place, when you want great nuts versus cinnamon toast crunch.

04:17.951 --> 04:28.405
You see, you don't care about the price or the ingredients, maybe even how long it's been on the shelf, or if you shouldn't be eating all that sugar like your doctor told you to.

04:29.306 --> 04:37.778
You walk in intending to be wise, but you actually walk out with a cart full of junk food or a pint of ice cream so you can eat and watch your favorite show.

04:38.754 --> 04:44.101
And all you had did was pick what was available to you and ready for you right now.

04:44.722 --> 04:58.721
You see, when we are really hungry for the right now or thirsty, you most want what you don't need and most need what you don't want.

04:59.803 --> 05:02.807
It's like this with our relational appetite too.

05:02.827 --> 05:07.954
Like an unintentional trip to the grocery store, when you're starving, you will settle.

05:09.154 --> 05:15.983
Whether you are single, dating, married, struggling, or even grieving a loss, hear me.

05:16.624 --> 05:18.387
You are not a product.

05:19.468 --> 05:33.868
You are not here to be sampled, nor to treat others like a Costco sample to also be browsed, or evaluated to make sure that the use by date, like a can of spam, is okay.

05:35.390 --> 05:38.514
In the kingdom of God, dating is not shopping.

05:38.946 --> 05:39.827
It's discipleship.

05:40.628 --> 05:57.487
God has more for you than trying the latest skew of that person or that person so that they can be all that you think that you want them or need them to be to make your life whole or for you to make someone else's life whole.

05:58.969 --> 06:06.578
Well, how do we not give into that temptation to treat people that way or even allow ourselves to be treated in that way?

06:07.586 --> 06:17.475
The scripture says this in Proverbs 4, 23, above all else guard your heart for everything you do flows from it.

06:18.456 --> 06:21.299
The Hebrew word for heart is left.

06:21.319 --> 06:28.005
Now this doesn't just mean butterflies like the hallmark movies or your romantic feelings.

06:28.145 --> 06:31.408
It refers to the mission control center of your life.

06:32.069 --> 06:37.554
It's the place where you think, decide, choose, and trust.

06:39.234 --> 06:48.365
Now in the modern view, the heart is often referred to or the lev is primarily associated with feelings and romance.

06:50.008 --> 06:56.776
It's seen as the emotional center, the place from which our desires and our passions flow.

06:58.098 --> 07:04.786
And as a result of that, the stability is only mood based and it's constantly changing.

07:05.378 --> 07:13.007
It's depending on circumstances, chemistry, or even emotional highs and lows.

07:13.027 --> 07:19.395
The prevailing cultural advice is to follow your heart, or you think of frozen.

07:19.935 --> 07:20.957
Love is an open door.

07:22.278 --> 07:26.323
Implying that your feelings are the most trustworthy guide.

07:27.244 --> 07:30.368
The scriptures also say that the heart is deceitful and wicked.

07:31.069 --> 07:32.050
Nobody can know it.

07:33.218 --> 07:39.264
which in line with the contrast of the biblical view of the heart, the Lev in Hebrew is much deeper.

07:39.624 --> 07:43.208
It refers to our will, our thoughts, and our choices.

07:43.829 --> 07:49.454
It's not just the seat of emotion, but it's actually the control center of your life.

07:49.795 --> 07:56.021
Biblically, the heart is meant to be a steady foundation from which everything that you do flows from.

07:56.702 --> 08:01.106
That is why scripture does not tell us to follow our heart.

08:02.082 --> 08:08.550
but instead it tells us to guard it, to guard it and set it fully upon God.

08:10.492 --> 08:16.339
We have heard it said, follow your heart or listen to your heart, but the scripture says actually something different.

08:16.620 --> 08:23.808
It says to guard it because what you do not guard will be taken and it will be twisted.

08:25.010 --> 08:31.858
For example, you would not hire a security guard to guard a pile of trash.

08:33.378 --> 08:39.003
What flows through your heart will eventually start to shape your habits.

08:40.064 --> 08:45.730
You would not put a security detail on something that's not a value.

08:45.950 --> 08:49.833
You would only put a security detail on something that is a value.

08:50.374 --> 08:52.716
I have never taken out the trash.

08:53.297 --> 08:54.618
Now my wife would be like, yes.

08:57.240 --> 09:03.346
I've never taken out the trash, pulled out my cell phone, and called the police and asked them to watch a pile of trash.

09:04.610 --> 09:12.239
You see, I would call the police to protect me or my family or my loved ones that I value who are important to me.

09:13.341 --> 09:15.343
We do not guard trash.

09:16.204 --> 09:18.667
We actually guard treasure.

09:20.309 --> 09:28.179
God instructs us that through the writers of the Bible to guard what is of extreme value.

09:29.000 --> 09:30.482
That is your heart.

09:31.906 --> 09:37.394
in all seasons, in every type of relationship, we are to guard our hearts, especially in dating.

09:38.195 --> 09:49.951
Not just when we are dating, but also when we are single, and not just when we're single, also when we are married, and then not also when we are also widows or widowers.

09:50.292 --> 09:52.375
God's wisdom applies to all of us.

09:53.156 --> 09:57.522
You see, a love that is worth waiting for applies to all people

09:58.370 --> 10:03.598
But in the context of this talk today, we're dealing primarily with romantic relationships.

10:04.779 --> 10:14.374
To the single and dating, guard your love, your heart from the beginning, from becoming desperate for attention.

10:15.696 --> 10:24.989
Give your heart away and be focused on what you are becoming and who you are becoming versus what you can get.

10:26.211 --> 10:28.274
And to the married, guard your love.

10:28.546 --> 10:37.374
your heart when you are tempted to rewrite your covenant based on a difficult season of frustration within your marriage.

10:38.095 --> 10:40.697
Or to the grieving, guard your love.

10:41.798 --> 10:46.183
Your heart still belongs to God because your heart is a treasure.

10:47.003 --> 10:48.184
It's not a trash can.

10:49.786 --> 10:55.591
Now, if you've never heard the story of Ruth, this story begins in a time of chaos and in hunger.

10:56.212 --> 10:58.354
A man named

10:58.914 --> 11:07.662
Ilamilik looks at his wife Naomi and their two sons in Bethlehem and sees that they are starving.

11:08.643 --> 11:13.428
So desperate to provide, he goes and he moves them to a land called Moab.

11:13.468 --> 11:16.451
It's a foreign country and it's a land of foreign gods.

11:17.212 --> 11:25.099
But on the grocery run to Moab, it will cost him and it will cost his family more than they ever could have imagined.

11:26.781 --> 11:27.922
Emily dies.

11:28.866 --> 11:35.617
And then the two sons who had married local women named Orpa and Ruth also died.

11:36.319 --> 11:43.390
And in 10 short years, Naomi goes from a full house to an empty one.

11:43.410 --> 11:48.840
She's left in a foreign land with no husband, no sons, no security.

11:48.860 --> 11:55.090
And then when Naomi hears that the famine has ended back home, she decides to return.

11:55.586 --> 12:01.293
But she looks at her daughters-in-law and pleads with them to stay in Moab.

12:02.395 --> 12:06.620
She tells them, go back to your mothers and find rest in new homes.

12:07.141 --> 12:12.388
I have nothing left to give you, no more sons to marry, no hope to offer you.

12:13.309 --> 12:16.152
My life has become bitter.

12:17.154 --> 12:22.601
Now Orpa weeps kisses Naomi and then goes back to her comfort.

12:22.621 --> 12:23.602
But what does Ruth do?

12:24.610 --> 12:31.156
Ruth does something that actually defies logic.

12:31.176 --> 12:38.483
While Naomi tries to push her way for her own good, Ruth refuses to move.

12:39.684 --> 12:45.910
She doesn't just say, all of a sudden, I need to go with you.

12:46.851 --> 12:48.773
No, the text says that she clung to her.

12:49.293 --> 12:54.418
Naomi points to Orpa walking away and says,

12:55.010 --> 12:57.914
Your sister is going away back to her gods.

12:58.055 --> 12:58.676
Go with her.

12:59.857 --> 13:02.742
But Ruth has already made her choice.

13:02.762 --> 13:04.945
She isn't looking for a shortcut.

13:04.965 --> 13:06.788
She's looking to honor God.

13:07.229 --> 13:13.198
You see, Ruth was starving for a new life, just like Orpa.

13:14.239 --> 13:23.794
But while Orpa went back to what was easy and familiar, Ruth decided that she would rather starve in a field with God

13:23.970 --> 13:31.098
The God of Israel then to feast in a palace of the gods of Moab.

13:31.118 --> 13:34.742
She chose character over comfort.

13:35.563 --> 13:49.478
She chose to guard her left, her heart, to commit her life to serving with commitment before she even knew that there was a man named Boaz who was actually waiting for her.

13:49.999 --> 13:53.042
Some of you are like, yes, that's a word, Lord.

13:54.498 --> 13:58.683
You see, here in the story, Ruth begins with heartbreak and hunger.

13:59.363 --> 14:03.668
But in chapter one of Ruth, she becomes a widow in a foreign land.

14:04.289 --> 14:08.674
She has recently lost her husband, her security, and her future.

14:09.595 --> 14:12.057
And she's starving for hope.

14:12.077 --> 14:17.483
But look at how she responds to Naomi about the wreckage of her life in verse 16.

14:18.204 --> 14:23.410
But Ruth replied, don't urge me to leave you or to turn back from you.

14:24.418 --> 14:27.121
Where you go, I will go.

14:27.301 --> 14:29.744
And where you stay, I will stay.

14:30.264 --> 14:32.586
Your people will be my people.

14:33.267 --> 14:35.229
And your God, my God.

14:36.450 --> 14:40.635
You see, this is a statement, not just of sentiment.

14:40.655 --> 14:43.237
It's a declaration of what we call a covenant.

14:43.698 --> 14:49.544
The Hebrew word, it's not explicitly mentioned, but it's communicated from Ruth.

14:49.684 --> 14:51.506
And this concept called has said,

14:51.874 --> 14:57.262
which is a covenantal steadfast love, a loyal love, she says.

14:57.903 --> 15:00.226
My life for yours.

15:01.648 --> 15:04.512
Ruth doesn't run after immediate comfort.

15:04.832 --> 15:08.197
She chooses to serve versus being served.

15:09.339 --> 15:13.405
Ruth works in the margins, cleaning from the scraps of the field.

15:14.366 --> 15:18.272
Eventually, a landowner, a man named Boaz notices her.

15:19.553 --> 15:19.954
Ruth

15:20.290 --> 15:28.461
2, 11 through 12, Boas replied to her, I've been told about what you have done for your mother-in-law.

15:29.462 --> 15:34.669
Since the death of your husband, may the Lord repay you for what you have done.

15:35.971 --> 15:44.402
May you richly be rewarded by the Lord under whose wings you have come to take refuge.

15:45.570 --> 15:47.833
You see, Ruth wasn't in her best clothes.

15:48.013 --> 15:49.075
She didn't have her hair did.

15:49.095 --> 15:50.677
She didn't have her makeup on.

15:51.738 --> 15:54.402
She wasn't even seeking to be noticed.

15:56.505 --> 15:57.306
But please hear me.

15:57.827 --> 16:12.306
This is not a message about me saying, don't try to be presentable before others or those who you might even be interested in a relationship or to think that I'm saying that relationships don't require, don't require any effort because they do.

16:12.994 --> 16:25.644
What I want to encourage you in is that God is always present in the work which he knows what you need regardless of certain circumstances that you may be experiencing.

16:26.947 --> 16:28.370
This is not a message

16:28.546 --> 16:37.900
about trying to be presentable or to what others we think that we are interested in, because look, listen, God does not require any effort.

16:37.980 --> 16:44.049
He does not require you to fix yourself up before you can come to him, before he loves you.

16:44.710 --> 16:48.997
The reality is, is that God is always present in the work.

16:49.658 --> 16:51.841
He knows what you need.

16:52.963 --> 16:57.810
He knows what you are desiring.

16:58.466 --> 17:01.250
because he knows the circumstances that you may be experiencing.

17:02.212 --> 17:06.638
Now, before Boaz saw Ruth in the field, God saw her in a famine.

17:07.119 --> 17:09.843
Boaz didn't fall for a spark.

17:09.923 --> 17:12.527
He didn't say, hey, man, woo, woo, wow.

17:13.609 --> 17:15.231
He recognized her spirit.

17:15.271 --> 17:19.738
He recognized the woman of Hasid, a woman of commitment, of character.

17:19.798 --> 17:27.570
He saw a woman of character and who she was and who she was becoming in the midst of the brokenness in her life.

17:28.066 --> 17:33.012
This shows us a lot of how Jesus shows us His love.

17:33.032 --> 17:38.979
That regardless of how we may not look put together, our lives are falling apart.

17:39.359 --> 17:43.284
That doesn't throw Jesus off from loving us and serving us.

17:43.304 --> 17:47.249
He doesn't look at us and say, man, y'all look raggedy, let me run the opposite way.

17:48.450 --> 17:50.092
That's not the way that God responds.

17:51.714 --> 17:55.218
What would our lives look like if we didn't exist

17:55.362 --> 18:04.215
completely for ourselves, but we were committed to others for the growth of discipleship and others for people becoming the people of God.

18:05.077 --> 18:19.458
See, God wants us to help in the discipleship of seeing God, of people become the people that God wants them to be versus the people that we want to change them to be, the way that we want so that they can serve our needs.

18:20.500 --> 18:22.002
So to my single friends today,

18:23.906 --> 18:25.488
who would like to be in a relationship.

18:27.051 --> 18:29.495
Don't just look for feelings.

18:29.515 --> 18:31.037
Look for covenant character.

18:32.098 --> 18:33.741
Not shadow compatibility.

18:34.903 --> 18:43.496
Like Phil spoke about last week, if the goal is to be together for the rest of your lives, don't just look for vibes.

18:43.536 --> 18:45.839
Don't just try to catch the butterflies.

18:47.802 --> 18:49.986
Don't just let those things catch your attention.

18:50.987 --> 18:52.850
Let the right character

18:53.026 --> 18:53.867
catch your attention.

18:54.087 --> 19:09.702
The character that will strengthen true commitment into my married friends has said this covenantal keeping love is the oxygen that your marriage needs when the feeling of love runs love.

19:11.464 --> 19:22.194
And to my friends who have lost a spouse, I want to encourage you today to look to God to continue to give you the wisdom and build trust

19:22.978 --> 19:31.790
in Him that even if you don't know what's next, that He knows that He is working in you for your behalf.

19:33.151 --> 19:38.979
And to my single friends who have no desire for any relationship, you're like, nope, I'm good, I'm fine by myself.

19:40.581 --> 19:50.354
Submit your heart to God and guard it from actually becoming a life that is lived, focused inwardly on self.

19:51.042 --> 19:54.967
but to be open on how you are to serve others with your life.

19:56.189 --> 19:59.974
Now, in the story of Ruth, we come to something called the Threshing Floor.

20:00.375 --> 20:02.437
Now, this is a place of testing.

20:03.178 --> 20:12.010
In biblical times, grain was tossed in through the air so that the wind would blow and it would separate the heavy grain from the useless shaft.

20:13.352 --> 20:16.677
Now, it was a place of separation.

20:17.898 --> 20:20.562
And Ruth 3 9 through 11, Boas says this,

20:20.930 --> 20:22.412
Who are you?"

20:22.533 --> 20:23.113
He asked.

20:24.335 --> 20:26.178
She said, I am your servant Ruth.

20:26.879 --> 20:28.021
I could just imagine the place.

20:28.442 --> 20:29.483
I'm your servant Ruth.

20:31.126 --> 20:39.619
She said, spread the corner of your garment over me, since you are the guardian Redeemer, which also means kinsman Redeemer of our family.

20:41.082 --> 20:43.886
The Lord bless you, my God, her, he replied.

20:44.307 --> 20:49.074
The kindness, this kindness is greater, which you have showed earlier.

20:49.890 --> 20:56.859
You do not have to, you have not run after the younger men, whether rich or poor.

20:58.140 --> 21:00.043
And now my daughter, don't be afraid.

21:00.984 --> 21:03.927
I will do for you all that you ask.

21:04.668 --> 21:10.055
All the people in the town know that you are a woman of noble character.

21:11.657 --> 21:19.026
See, Ruth is asking Boas to step into his calling as what's called a kinsman redeemer.

21:19.138 --> 21:25.947
They are alone in the dark, culturally, and in this culture, this is a high pressure moment.

21:26.628 --> 21:31.074
But look at Boaz's restraint in Ruth 3, 12 through 13.

21:31.815 --> 21:39.866
Although it is true that I am your kinsman Redeemer of the family, there is another who was more closely related than I.

21:40.687 --> 21:48.658
Stay here for the night and in the morning, if he wants to do his duty as your kinsman Redeemer,

21:49.026 --> 21:50.648
Let him redeem you.

21:51.530 --> 21:56.637
But if he is not willing, as surely as the Lord lives, I will do it.

21:57.118 --> 21:58.480
Lie here until the morning.

21:59.782 --> 22:03.267
Now in these verses, it highlights this concept called a kinsmen redeemer.

22:04.209 --> 22:07.393
In ancient Israel, land was the lifeblood.

22:07.634 --> 22:11.840
A family's future was also connected to this.

22:12.621 --> 22:15.826
So when a man died without an heir,

22:16.514 --> 22:27.246
Just as Naomi's husbands and sons had, the family land would typically be sold to outsiders and the family name would be erased from history.

22:27.266 --> 22:39.939
This is where the word go-el or the kinsmen redeemer steps in holding the unique right and responsibility to redeem or to buy back the land so it actually stayed within the family.

22:40.540 --> 22:46.226
And then to marry the widow of the deceased relative to actually provide an heir.

22:47.490 --> 22:49.874
You see, this wasn't just a romantic gesture.

22:50.515 --> 22:57.846
This was a rescue mission for a family line that was starving on the verge of extinction.

22:58.588 --> 23:02.514
Now, when we ask if Boaz, does he actually have to do this?

23:02.874 --> 23:06.600
The answer, the technical answer is no, he was not forced to do this.

23:07.261 --> 23:15.314
Because while the law of the kinsmen Redeemer actually existed, it was often viewed as a very, very heavy burden.

23:15.778 --> 23:22.925
due to the significant financial cost of buying back land out of his own pocket.

23:22.945 --> 23:43.826
Furthermore, it actually involved an estate dilution because any children of Boaz with Ruth would legally belong to the line of the deceased husband, meaning that the land of Boaz would actually eventually go to Ruth's sons rather than Boaz's own existing heirs.

23:44.994 --> 23:51.304
You see, this is exactly why the closer relative in Ruth 4, 6, refused it.

23:51.745 --> 23:55.751
He refused to do it stating, I cannot redeem it.

23:55.911 --> 24:01.861
I cannot do this for Ruth because I might endanger my own estate.

